                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                      CM prod for heat relief
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                          Chief minister Naveen Patnaik at a review meeting in the secretariat on Monday. (Sanjib Mukherjee)                                  
	Bhubaneswar, April 26: The severe heat wave condition in the state, which has claimed 21 lives, today forced chief minister Naveen Patnaik to take stock of the situation.        
	Instructions have been issued to departments concerned to take necessary action to tackle the situation, Patnaik told reporters after chairing the meeting in the afternoon.        
	The state had earlier directed closure of schools for summer vacations from April 20. The summer vacation was initially scheduled to start from May 1.        
	According to the state disaster management minister Surya Narayan Patro, 21 persons have died of sunstroke this summer. The highest number of casualty (three) has been reported from Ganjam  the chief ministers home district.         
	As many as 117 reports of sunstroke deaths had reached the state disaster management department, out of which 21 were confirmed following joint inquiry by health and disaster management departments.         
	Severe heat wave has been sweeping across the state for the past few weeks, with the mercury hovering above 40 degrees Celsius at several places.        
	Todays highest temperature  43.5C  was recorded at Talcher, followed by Jharsuguda (43.3C), Sambalpur (43.2C), Angul (43.1C) and Titlagarh (43C), while the mercury hovered above 40C at Bolangir, Hirakud, Sundargarh, Bhawaniptana, and Keonjhar.        
	As the scorching heat has caused severe shortage of drinking water, chief minister today instructed officials to ensure adequate water supply in problem areas.        
	Energy department officials were asked not to cut off electricity supply to pipe water supply projects.        
	The special relief commissioner was directed to release financial assistance from the contingency fund to repair burnt electricity transfers, said Patro.        
	Steps taken by related departments to tackle the heat wave were also reviewed by the chief minister, he said.                                                                                                                                                          
